}}
'''Umhlanga lagoon''' is a {{convert|26|ha}} [[nature reserve]] on the shore of the [[Indian Ocean]] at [[Umhlanga, KwaZulu-Natal|Umhlanga Rocks]], [[South Africa]].{{sfn|Bainbridge|2010|p=}} The reserve encloses the [[Ohlanga River]]'s lagoon and mouth.{{sfn|Ballard|1998|p=}} The forest forms a natural extension of the less accessible [[Hawaan Forest]], of which the greater part lies inland of the busy [[M4 road (Durban)|M4 road]]. The reserve trails start at a car park at the northern end of Lagoon Drive, Umhlanga.

The reserve has picnic sites, the remains of a prehistoric [[shell midden]]{{sfn|Beater|Maud|1963}} and walking trails,{{sfn|Ballard|1998|p=}} with a walkway and pedestrian bridge that span the lagoon.

At the mouth of the Ohlanga lagoon there is a popular but unofficial [[nudist beach]].{{sfn|Steele|2012|p=234}}<ref name="phoe_Unco" /><ref name="nort_uMhl" /> Increased use of the area by non-nudist walkers and families resulted in complaints about nudism and antisocial behaviour.<ref name ="Anthony2013" /> The area was at one time a ‘no-go’ area, due to a serious crime problem.<ref name ="Anthony2013" />
The use of this area by naturists is under threat as the [[eThekwini Metropolitan Municipality]] is planning a clamp down on nudity in Durban.<ref name="time_Zipi" />

