[[File:Étagère.png|thumb|upright|An étagère for candies]]
[[Image:Etagere.png|thumb|upright|An étagère for decorative objects]]
An '''étagère''' or '''shelf''' is a French set of hanging or standing open [[shelf (storage)|shelves]] for the display of collections of objects or ornaments.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1o3WLC1WuX8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Dictionary of Architecture and Interior Design|last=Gilliatt|first=Mary|date=1 October 2012|publisher=Pan|isbn=978-1-74334-067-7|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3FjAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Fairchild Books Dictionary of Interior Design|last=Hinchman|first=Mark|date=2 January 2014|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-60901-534-3|language=en}}</ref>

The étagère became a popular form of furniture in the nineteenth century.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/works-of-art/1999.50.2/|title=Etagere {{!}} Work of Art {{!}} Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History {{!}} The Metropolitan Museum of Art|website=The Met's Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History|access-date=29 November 2016}}</ref> Similar to the [[what-not]], the shelves of the étagère provided extra space for the display of the accumulation of knickknacks that was typical of [[Victorian decorative arts|Victorian home decor]].<ref name=":0" />

